<DOC><DOCNO> AP890317-0146 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 1843EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-17 0531</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0544</SECOND><HEAD>Heavy Snow In Upper Midwest, Record Warmth In East</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Cold air surging into the north-central part of the nationproduced heavy snow Friday over parts of the upper Midwest, whilesections of the East had unseasonably warm weather.   Snow fell from the northern High Plains through the middleMissouri Valley to Michigan during the afternoon, with heavy snowacross parts of South Dakota and Wisconsin.   Snowfall totals in Minnesota ranged up to 7.5 inches atFarmington by mid morning and up to a foot of snow was expected toblanket central Wisconsin by Saturday morning.   The snow was expected to spread across the upper Great Lakesregion into northern New England, and a winter storm watch wasposted for Saturday for northern Vermont and northeastern New Yorkstate.   South of the snow belt, a mixture of snow, sleet and freezingrain extended across northern Iowa, southern Wisconsin and northernIllinois, and showers and thunderstorms spread over parts of centralIllinois.   Strong, gusty wind blew across the central Rockies and thecentral high Plains during the morning, with gusts to 85 mphreported in the Loveland ski area of Colorado and gusts to 58 mph inNebraska at Scottsbluff and Sydney.   A low pressure system off the northern Pacific Coast producedlight showers over western Oregon and northern California, with snowat higher elevations of western Oregon.   Elsewhere, southern Florida had light showers.   A cold front curving through the central and eastern part of thenation created a sharp contrast in temperatures.   Afternoon temperatures were generally below freezing from thenorthern Rockies through the northern and central Plains to northernNew England. And readings were only in the teens and single digitsfrom Montana through the Dakotas to Upper Michigan and northernLower Michigan.   Ahead of the front, temperatures were generally in the 70s and80s across the south-central and southeastern states.   Boston tied its record of 66 degrees, and in West Virginia,Beckley warmed to a record 73 and Huntington hit a record 76.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 7degrees at Cut Bank, Mont., Warroad, Minn., and Watertown, S.D., to88 at McAllen, Texas. Friday's low for the Lower 48 states was 24degrees below zero at Hibbing, Minn.   For Saturday, rain was forecast from the upper Ohio Valley andthe lower Great Lakes region across the middle and northern AtlanticCoast states, with snow and freezing rain in northern New England.Scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast over the lowerMississippi Valley and the central Gulf Coast states. Snow wasforecast over the northern Rockies and the northern high Plains, andscattered showers were forecast across the northern and centralPacific Coast region.   Highs in the 20s and lower 30s were predicted from Montanathrough Minnesota to Upper Michigan, and across northern Maine; inthe 40s from the central Rockies through the middle and upperMississippi Valley to northern New England; above 70 from southernCalifornia through southern and central Texas to the southern andmiddle Atlantic Coast region; and in the 80s in the desert Southwestand from south-central Texas to Florida and southern Georgia.</TEXT></DOC>